Universities and campuses became another front in this struggle over dissent. At Columbia, student protesters against the war in Gaza occupied a library and were arrested. Four student journalists who covered the protests were briefly suspended. Elsewhere, the State Department directed university officers to report international students and scholars involved in protests deemed antisemitic or linked to terrorism. At the same time, ICE obtained a search warrant for Columbia student housing by telling a judge it needed evidence that the university was \'93harboring aliens,\'94 then used that warrant to try to arrest two pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian students. One of them, a legal permanent resident, has sued, arguing that the warrant was obtained under false pretenses. These moves did not ban protest outright. They made it riskier for non\u8209 citizens and for institutions that depend on federal funds and visas, pushing universities to police speech to avoid trouble.\
